   341â†’
   342â†’Key aspects of this pattern:
   343â†’
   344â†’- **`toolChoice: 'required'`**: Forces the model to call a tool at every step instead of generating text directly. This ensures the agent follows a structured workflow.
   345â†’- **`done` tool without `execute`**: A tool that has no `execute` function acts as a termination signal. When the agent calls this tool, the loop stops because there's no function to execute.
   346â†’- **Accessing results**: The final answer is available in `result.staticToolCalls`, which contains tool calls that weren't executed.
   347â†’
   348â†’This pattern is useful when you want the agent to always use specific tools for operations (like code execution or data retrieval) rather than attempting to answer directly.
   349â†’
   350â†’## Manual Loop Control
   351â†’
   352â†’For scenarios requiring complete control over the agent loop, you can use AI SDK Core functions (`generateText` and `streamText`) to implement your own loop management instead of using `stopWhen` and `prepareStep`. This approach provides maximum flexibility for complex workflows.
   353â†’
   354â†’### Implementing a Manual Loop
   355â†’
   356â†’Build your own agent loop when you need full control over execution:
   357â†’
   358â†’```ts
   359â†’import { generateText, ModelMessage } from 'ai';
   360â†’__PROVIDER_IMPORT__;
   361â†’
   362â†’const messages: ModelMessage[] = [{ role: 'user', content: '...' }];
   363â†’
   364â†’let step = 0;
   365â†’const maxSteps = 10;
   366â†’
   367â†’while (step < maxSteps) {
   368â†’  const result = await generateText({
   369â†’    model: __MODEL__,
   370â†’    messages,
   371â†’    tools: {
   372â†’      // your tools here
   373â†’    },
   374â†’  });
   375â†’
   376â†’  messages.push(...result.response.messages);
   377â†’
   378â†’  if (result.text) {
   379â†’    break; // Stop when model generates text
   380â†’  }
   381â†’
   382â†’  step++;
   383â†’}
   384â†’```
   385â†’
   386â†’This manual approach gives you complete control over:
   387â†’
   388â†’- Message history management
   389â†’- Step-by-step decision making
   390â†’- Custom stopping conditions
   391â†’- Dynamic tool and model selection
   392â†’- Error handling and recovery
